Test suite (port of `test/parse.test.ts`, template half) exercising `steno::parse_template` against the `Chunk`/`Expr` types; the counterpart `parse_template_edit.rs` (or similarly named file) likely ports the pattern half. Not itself depended on by other files, but it pins the exact chunk grammar and error-message wording that `parse_template` must produce — changing chunk variants, `Expr` fields, or error text in the parser will break these literal `assert_eq!`/substring checks.

Key grammar facts encoded here (load-bearing, easy to break unknowingly): landings are single-digit only (`%12` → `Landing(1)` + literal `"2"`, not `Landing(12)`); `{`/`}` become `Chunk::Brace{open}` while `%b` is a separate `Chunk::BodyBreak`; escapes `\{ \} \% \\ \` ` collapse to literal text, while `\n`/`\t` become dedicated `Chunk::Newline`/`Chunk::Tab` chunks (not literals); a bare `|` outside `%[...%]` is just literal text; `%[sep|body%]` splits on the first top-level `|`, and omitting the pipe yields an empty `sep` vec; repeats nest arbitrarily. Computed expressions (`%(...)`) parse a small linear-expression grammar into `Expr{a, b}`, supporting bare `d`, coefficients, signs, sign-only (`-d`), constant-only (`%(5)` → `a:0,b:5`), and internal whitespace — all forms must map to specific `a`/`b` values shown in `computed_expressions`.

The `template_errors` test locks specific error substrings ("unknown operator %z", "trailing '%'", "trailing backslash", "unknown escape \\q", "unterminated %[", "unterminated %(", "bad computed expression") — renaming or rewording these in the parser's error construction will fail this test even if behavior is otherwise correct. All `parse_template` calls here use indent width `1` (second arg), irrelevant to these particular assertions but required by the signature.